      conceptExplanation: "These ownership types developed because cities became crowded — people wanted ownership, not just renting, but shared buildings needed shared costs. CONDOMINIUMS (NRS 117): Each owner holds fee simple title to their individual unit (can sell, mortgage, will it) and shares ownership of common areas (hallways, elevators, roof, pool, land) as tenants in common. Created by recording a Condominium Declaration + Plat Map. CC&Rs govern use (parking, exterior changes, pets). Each unit has its own tax bill and mortgage — foreclosure only affects that unit. The Owners' Association (HOA) manages the building and collects monthly assessments. COOPERATIVES (rare in NV): A corporation owns the building. Buyers purchase shares of stock (personal property, NOT real estate) and receive a proprietary lease for a specific unit. Co-op boards can screen and reject buyers — unlike condos. Major risk: if enough shareholders stop paying fees, the corporation defaults and the entire building faces foreclosure — everyone loses their interest. TIME-SHARES: Estate = fee simple ownership for specific time periods (e.g., Weeks 1-2 every June forever). Use = contractual right to occupy that expires (e.g., Weeks 1-2 in June for 10 years). Heavily regulated under NRS/NAC 119A due to high-pressure sales tactics and consumer protection needs.",
